WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.400
Thanks to all of you who've signed on for this, which is my first RStudio webinar.

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:26.400
I'm going to talk about the package readxl, which I've recently done a maintenance release

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:34.279
on, and I want to talk a little bit about our sticker for readxl.

00:00:34.279 --> 00:00:40.520
RStudio and many other package-producing entities have started to create these hex stickers

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:44.959
so that you can show your love for packages, and the one we made for readxl is supposed

00:00:44.959 --> 00:00:49.919
to capture that really special feeling you get when you find out that the data you need

00:00:49.919 --> 00:00:51.959
is actually in Excel.

00:00:51.959 --> 00:00:56.200
So hopefully if you want one of these, you can find one of us in person at some meeting

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:57.560
and maybe we'll have them.

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:01.000
You can put them on your laptop to show your suffering.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:11.440
So readxl is a package that finds itself inside a larger group of packages, which we're calling

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:17.400
the Tidyverse, and this I believe is still a subset of the Tidyverse, but the idea of

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:23.720
the Tidyverse is to take a collection of packages and make sure that they operate with a common

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:31.320
philosophy and a really similar interface so that it's easy to transfer expertise from

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:32.800
one package to the other.

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:41.480
It's easy to move objects from one package to another, and so readxl is the Tidyverse

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:49.440
solution for getting data out of Excel spreadsheets and into R. You see the URL for the website

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:50.440
up there.

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:55.400
It's still, I'd call it, sort of under development, but we're adding more and more packages to

00:01:55.400 --> 00:02:00.800
it, and then we're increasingly adding content on the Tidyverse itself.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:06.400
So it's certainly absolutely worth visiting at this point, and you can expect that to

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:12.039
increase in sort of quality and coverage over time.

00:02:12.039 --> 00:02:19.360
Another really important sort of documentation, I would say, for the Tidyverse is there's

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:25.000
a recent book, although it's been online for quite a while, by Hadley Wickham and Garrett

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.279
Grolamund, both of our studio, called R for Data Science, and in some sense it's a meta-manual

00:02:32.279 --> 00:02:38.399
for the Tidyverse, or you will certainly see the Tidyverse packages working in their natural

00:02:38.399 --> 00:02:43.240
environment and working in concert with each other throughout that book.

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:48.600
So it's a really good resource, and you can buy a physical book, or if you go to this

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:53.759
URL that I'm showing there, it has always been developed in the open, and you can always

00:02:53.759 --> 00:02:58.279
access the content online for free.

00:02:58.279 --> 00:03:04.119
And below I have a graphic that we see in a lot of talks by Hadley and other people

00:03:04.119 --> 00:03:10.800
who develop or work in the Tidyverse that's meant to depict a typical data science and

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:14.240
data analysis workflow.

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:19.759
And Read Excel is one of the packages we have to deal with that very first step, which

00:03:19.759 --> 00:03:27.399
is importing data out of a spreadsheet and getting it into R in a favorable form to sort

00:03:27.399 --> 00:03:34.080
of fly through the rest of this cycle at least as easily as possible.

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:37.300
A little bit of history on Read Excel.

00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:44.539
So it was first released on CRAN in April of 2015, and that release was written entirely

00:03:44.539 --> 00:03:49.580
by Hadley, and then about a year later it had a patch release, which I think was just

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:55.100
triggered by the need to update for compatibility with the package, so that didn't have a lot

00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:56.940
of changes in it.

00:03:56.940 --> 00:04:03.979
And so then it got its first major maintenance release about a month ago, which is when I

00:04:04.139 --> 00:04:08.979
took over as the new maintainer and we moved the version up to one.

00:04:08.979 --> 00:04:15.619
I feel like it is pretty feature complete, and we squashed lots of bugs and added a few

00:04:15.619 --> 00:04:21.619
new features, which I will talk about today.

00:04:21.619 --> 00:04:25.459
And in case you want to install it in the background while I chatter on a little bit

00:04:25.459 --> 00:04:27.100
more.

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:33.179
So one way to get Read Excel installed on your computer is to install the entire Tidyverse.

00:04:33.179 --> 00:04:37.820
So we now have a package called Tidyverse, which is kind of different from the concept

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:38.820
of the Tidyverse.

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:47.220
It's a meta package that will install the whole set of packages on your computer, or

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:49.899
you could install Read Excel all by itself.

00:04:49.899 --> 00:04:53.540
So just install that package as Read Excel.

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:59.220
Then either way, you must load Read Excel individually.

00:04:59.779 --> 00:05:05.980
You can actually call library Tidyverse, and it will load a subset of the Tidyverse packages

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:08.420
that are kind of called the core.

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:13.140
And Read Excel is not part of that core, because you wouldn't need it in almost every analysis.

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:15.140
It's only when you have a spreadsheet.

00:05:15.140 --> 00:05:22.019
So you'll always have to load it explicitly on its own.

00:05:22.019 --> 00:05:27.859
So I promised in my abstract to give a little bit of the landscape of our packages that

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:31.019
Read Excel lives in.

00:05:31.019 --> 00:05:36.019
And the reason I wanted to do that is I figure anyone who's willing to spend an hour with

00:05:36.019 --> 00:05:43.420
us talking about Excel must have some slightly non-trivial need to read Excel files.

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:47.619
And it's kind of interesting just to know where the packages fit in and why some packages

00:05:47.619 --> 00:05:52.019
are harder to use than others or what the different features are.

00:05:52.019 --> 00:05:57.820
So there's a huge set of packages that read Excel files, because this has been an important

00:05:57.820 --> 00:06:00.260
area for a very long time, obviously.

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:08.140
So Read Excel might actually be the most recent entry into this group.

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:15.540
OpenXLSX is also fairly recent, and it uses a lot of the same stuff under the hood as

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:17.260
Read Excel.

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:26.420
Packages that have been around much longer are XLConnect, XLSX, and GData, RODBC.

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:30.859
And there are many more packages, some of which I link to actually from the readme of

00:06:30.859 --> 00:06:35.459
Read Excel itself for dealing with very awkward data.

00:06:35.459 --> 00:06:40.019
But so these are the ones probably that I consider the most comparable in terms of when

00:06:40.019 --> 00:06:44.700
people look up packages, what they are considering using.

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:48.779
So when you're thinking about where does Read Excel fit in and which of these packages

00:06:48.779 --> 00:06:55.140
are relevant to me, I think there's at least three things you need to consider.

00:06:55.140 --> 00:07:01.059
So one, there's two broad classes of Excel files.

00:07:01.059 --> 00:07:06.339
And unless someone's been evil, you'll be able to identify them from their file extension.

00:07:06.339 --> 00:07:10.660
So .xls are the older Excel files.

00:07:10.660 --> 00:07:13.899
In our documentation, we call them legacy files.

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:18.140
And those are files from Excel up to about 2007.

00:07:18.140 --> 00:07:23.260
But there's plenty of systems today that are still producing .xls files, and in fact, Excel

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:27.019
itself is still quite content to produce these files.

00:07:27.019 --> 00:07:33.660
And then the more modern file format is XLSX.

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:37.140
And that's what you're going to get by default coming out of Excel now.

00:07:37.140 --> 00:07:42.459
And again, there's lots of third-party tools that'll be writing these sorts of files.

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:47.380
So the main question to ask is not about the files, but it's about the R package.

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:51.380
And there's sort of two main categories of R packages.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:57.820
There are those that are self-contained versus the ones that have an external dependency.

00:07:57.820 --> 00:08:01.380
And I'll talk about this just for a second.

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:08.220
So neither of these file formats is something that you want to parse by hand, all by yourself

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:09.700
from the ground up.

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:15.579
So all of the packages that read Excel files are standing on the shoulders of others and

00:08:15.579 --> 00:08:21.739
have some sort of dependency where we're bringing in an existing library to parse the file.

00:08:21.739 --> 00:08:30.739
And it turns out that the most comprehensive package for doing that is a Java system called

00:08:30.739 --> 00:08:33.820
the Apache POI.

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:40.539
And so the packages that wrap Java have great functionality in the sense that you can almost

00:08:40.539 --> 00:08:47.020
say if Excel can read this file, this package can read it because of all the accumulated

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:50.700
conventional wisdom in Apache POI.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:56.340
And so that's why when you're writing an Excel reading package for R, it's very tempting

00:08:56.340 --> 00:09:01.539
to use Java because you can take advantage of this pretty amazing resource.

00:09:01.539 --> 00:09:06.940
And likewise, there are some sort of Perl scripts that have been around for a long time

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:10.460
that have a lot of smarts about reading Excel files.

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:14.299
And so we've taken another approach in ReadExcel, which is to bake everything you need into

00:09:14.299 --> 00:09:16.179
the package.

00:09:16.179 --> 00:09:21.619
And then the third huge component to think about is whether the package you're using

00:09:21.619 --> 00:09:30.099
is oriented towards bringing in a rectangular piece of data, so a data frame usually, or

00:09:30.179 --> 00:09:38.179
is it more focused on or capable of focusing on individual cells and formatting.

00:09:38.179 --> 00:09:41.900
So here's where ReadExcel comes out on all of these points.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:47.500
It is able to read XLS and XLSX.

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:48.940
It is self-contained.

00:09:48.940 --> 00:09:54.020
So once you get it installed, which should be relatively trivial, and definitely let

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:58.219
us know if it is not, it will just work.

00:09:58.340 --> 00:10:02.900
You don't need to configure an external dependency in the right place for it to work.

00:10:02.900 --> 00:10:07.500
And it is explicitly focused on bringing in a rectangle of data.

00:10:07.500 --> 00:10:13.020
So it is not a package that's going to reveal formatting for you, whereas some of those

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:14.020
others will.

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:20.020
So hopefully this gives you a sense of where Excel fits in.

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:26.340
I'm going to show you, this is a screenshot of one of the Excel workbooks that ships with

00:10:26.419 --> 00:10:29.940
the package, because I like to use it a lot in examples.

