And here's a screenshot right after I've brought that data set in.

00:13:28.299 --> 00:13:35.340
And we have a data frame in R. It's a TIBL, which is a special flavor of data frame that

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:41.140
is arguably the strongest theme that runs throughout the tidyverse.

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:45.500
So it prints very nicely, which we're enjoying right here.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:47.900
So you see we've got a TIBL that we brought in from Excel.

00:13:47.900 --> 00:13:48.900
It has 10 rows.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:50.979
It has six variables.

00:13:50.979 --> 00:13:56.739
And the thing I really want you to focus on is notice the types of the variables.

00:13:56.739 --> 00:14:01.500
That's one of the nice features of TIBL printing that you get to see these types.

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:06.299
So name and profession are character vectors.

00:14:06.299 --> 00:14:10.219
Age is double or numeric.

00:14:10.299 --> 00:14:14.260
Class kids is a logical vector, true or false.

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:18.099
Date of birth is a POSIX CT date time.

00:14:18.099 --> 00:14:23.700
And the code right above there actually brought this data set in, and you can see that I didn't

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:27.580
have to specify any of those column types.

00:14:27.580 --> 00:14:31.859
ReadExcel guessed them, and in this case, guessed them correctly.

00:14:31.859 --> 00:14:36.539
So I would describe readExcel's column typing as pretty groovy when it works.

00:14:36.539 --> 00:14:42.299
You can also take explicit control, which we'll show in the demo.

